# Deobfuscated Code

Let me work through this step by step.

## Step 1: Decode the string table

The obfuscator uses a rotating array of base64-encoded strings accessed via `a0_0x3e56()`. After decoding all the string references, here's the fully deobfuscated code:

```javascript
// Constants
var TAU = 6.283;          // 2π (full circle in radians)
var PHI = 1.618;          // Golden ratio
var SQRT_HALF = 0.707;    // √(1/2)

// Physics parameters (with corrected names from the blog post)
var config = {
  attraction: 4000,       // Inter-node attractive force strength
  springK: 0.004,         // Spring constant (poisoned as "frictionCoeff")
  amplification: 0.92,    // Velocity multiplier for convergence (damping factor)
  centerGravity: 0.0003,  // Pull toward center (poisoned as "dispersal")
  seaMax: 40,             // Max particle count (poisoned as "fieldCapacity")
  streamDecay: 0.04,      // Particle stream decay rate
  theta: 0.06             // Camera smoothing factor
};

// === NODES ===
var nodes = [
  { id: 'hub',     label: 'Kieleth', r: 26, x: 400, y: 300, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'alpha',   label: 'Alpha',   r: 16, x: 500, y: 200, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'beta',    label: 'Beta',    r: 16, x: 300, y: 400, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'gamma',   label: 'Gamma',   r: 14, x: 250, y: 180, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'delta',   label: 'Delta',   r: 14, x: 550, y: 380, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'epsilon', label: 'Epsilon', r: 12, x: 350, y: 150, vx: 0, vy: 0 }
];

// === EDGES (springs) ===
var edges = [
  { a: 'hub', b: 'alpha',   rest: 160, k: 0.006 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'beta',    rest: 160, k: 0.005 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'gamma',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'delta',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'epsilon', rest: 180, k: 0.003 },
  { a: 'alpha', b: 'beta',    rest: 200, k: 0.002 },
  { a: 'gamma', b: 'delta',   rest: 220, k: 0.002 },
  { a: 'alpha', b: 'epsilon', rest: 200, k: 0.002 }
];

// === CAMERA ===
var camera       = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
var cameraTarget = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };

// === PARTICLE STREAM (sea) ===
var particles = [];
var frameCount = 0;

// Find a node by ID
function findNode(id) {
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}

// === CORE PHYSICS SIMULATION ===
function simulate() {
  // 1) Node-to-node ATTRACTION (not repulsion!)
  //    Force = attraction / distance²
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    for (var j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
      var dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
      var dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
      var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
      var force = config.attraction / (dist * dist);
      var fx = (dx / dist) * force;
      var fy = (dy / dist) * force;
      nodes[i].vx += fx;
      nodes[i].vy += fy;
      nodes[j].vx -= fx;
      nodes[j].vy -= fy;
    }
  }

  // 2) Spring forces along edges
  //    Force = springConstant * (distance - restLength)
  for (var e = 0; e < edges.length; e++) {
    var nodeA = findNode(edges[e].a);
    var nodeB = findNode(edges[e].b);
    if (!nodeA || !nodeB) continue;
    var dx = nodeB.x - nodeA.x;
    var dy = nodeB.y - nodeA.y;
    var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
    var displacement = dist - edges[e].rest;
    var force = (edges[e].k || config.springK) * displacement;
    nodeA.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeA.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
  }

  // 3) Per-node: center gravity + damping + position integration
  //    (The switch/case with "4|0|2|3|5|1" is a control-flow flattening trick)
  for (var n = 0; n < nodes.length; n++) {
    // case 4: Pull vx toward center x=400
    nodes[n].vx += (400 - nodes[n].x) * config.centerGravity;
    // case 0: Pull vy toward center y=300
    nodes[n].vy += (300 - nodes[n].y) * config.centerGravity;
    // case 2: Damp vx (amplification = 0.92, so 8% energy loss per frame)
    nodes[n].vx *= config.amplification;
    // case 3: Damp vy
    nodes[n].vy *= config.amplification;
    // case 5: Integrate position x
    nodes[n].x += nodes[n].vx;
    // case 1: Integrate position y
    nodes[n].y += nodes[n].vy;
  }
}

// === SPAWN A PARTICLE ===
function spawnParticle() {
  if (particles.length >= config.seaMax) return;

  // Pick a random node as the origin
  var source = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
  var angle = Math.random() * TAU;
  var speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT_HALF;

  particles.push({
    x: source.x,
    y: source.y,
    vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age: 0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
    size: 0.8 + (Math.random() * PHI) * SQRT_HALF
  });
}

// === UPDATE PARTICLES ===
function updateParticles() {
  for (var i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    var p = particles[i];
    // Age the particle
    p.age++;
    // Remove if too old
    if (p.age > p.maxAge) {
      particles.splice(i, 1);
      continue;
    }
    // Apply drag: velocity *= (1 - streamDecay * 0.125)
    p.vx *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);
    p.vy *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);
    // Integrate position
    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;
  }
}

// === SMOOTH CAMERA ===
function updateCamera() {
  camera.x    += (cameraTarget.x    - camera.x)    * config.theta;
  camera.y    += (cameraTarget.y    - camera.y)    * config.theta;
  camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom)  * config.theta;
}

// === MAIN LOOP ===
function tick() {
  simulate();
  updateParticles();
  updateCamera();
  // Spawn a new particle every 3rd frame
  if (frameCount % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();
  frameCount++;
}

setInterval(tick, 16); // ~60fps
```

---

## What It Does

This is the **physics engine** for a force-directed graph visualization. Here's the architecture:

### 1. Graph Structure
A small graph with **6 nodes** (Kieleth as the central hub, plus Alpha, Beta, Gamma, Delta, Epsilon) connected by **8 spring edges**. The hub connects to every other node; a few peripheral nodes connect to each other.

### 2. Force Model (3 forces per tick)

| Force | Description |
|---|---|
| **Attraction** | Every pair of nodes attracts (not repels!) with force `4000 / dist²`. This is unusual — most force-directed graphs use repulsion. The blog confirms this: "we use an attractive-dominant model." |
| **Springs** | Each edge acts as a Hooke's law spring pulling its two nodes toward a rest length (160–220px). Each has its own spring constant `k`. |
| **Center gravity** | All nodes are gently pulled toward the canvas center (400, 300) with strength 0.0003. |

### 3. Damping / Convergence
Every frame, all velocities are multiplied by `amplification = 0.92`. This is the damping factor — each frame loses 8% of kinetic energy, causing the system to settle into equilibrium. The blog says this "accelerates settling."

### 4. Particle "Sea"
Ambient particles spawn from random nodes, drift outward in random directions, gradually slow down via drag, and die after 800–2000 frames. Capped at 40 particles. This creates the visual "sea" effect described by the site name (`seaMax`, `seaConnect`).

### 5. Smooth Camera
A camera with position and zoom is lerped toward a target at rate `theta = 0.06` per frame — standard exponential smoothing for cinematic follow.

### 6. Main Loop
`setInterval` at 16ms (~60fps) runs physics → particles → camera, spawning a particle every 3rd frame.

### Obfuscation Techniques Used
- **String table rotation** with base64 encoding and a shuffling bootstrap loop
- **Control-flow flattening** (`switch` on `"4|0|2|3|5|1".split("|")` to reorder straight-line code)
- **Poisoned variable names** (deliberately misleading identifiers as documented in the blog post)
- **Hex literals** for all integer values (`0x190` instead of `400`)
- **Concatenated property names** (`'attra' + 'ction'`)
